As stated at the start, this was intended to play similarly to a wlf, but with a bit more difficulty in not having the setup partially known. I didn't want to go too crazy, but I also wanted to put in some bits and pieces that might be tricky for players. The Drunk Seer with the shield was intended to be a personal problem for the player. They could protect themselves, but lose a check if they did, while knowing that their check might be drunk anyway. It doesn't make sense immediately, but if you can get the Wolves to waste a kill on you with the shield, then that's as powerful as a check, imo. Anyway, Diablo didn't use it and was drunk and immediately died, so lol. The Stalker had the pelt as protection, but would make them flag as Wolf to the Seer and should give BMC paranoia. The Beholder was strong here, in that they can still see the drunk checks of the DS and can help confirm the Stalker as not a Wolf. I know Beholders aren't used a lot anymore, so putting that in was to make people think about unusual roles and that it might just be BS because it isn't really a wlf role. The Blind Monk is a ridiculously strong role, but would get weaker as the game went on because the Wolves had the staff to spellbound people. The spellbound would also hell to weaken the Stalker. GD obviously was there to help try and sort stuff out. I put the rune on the sleepwalker as a hint towards spellbound that they might figure out, but gave them the wrong frigging rune boo hiss. The Lycan was obviously there as a Seer nerf. The Wolves only had three members, and I knew people might be expecting more, or possibly a BMC or two, so I wanted people to worry about Evils that didn't exist, and because the Village had only a few PRs, I felt three was the right number.
